I'm still working on the details, but I had an idea for a general code structure: I am going to start with a role phrase (such as "Krombacher is Villager") and encode the number that you get from adding up all of the letters (A=1, B=2, ..., Z=26) and taking the last two digits (e.g. "Krombacher is Villager" adds up to 94 + 28 + 86 = 208, so I would encode "8").
Then, knowing the target number and most of the phrase, you could plug in roles until you find the complete phrase that matches.
It's probably a little too cumbersome, though I'd love feedback on it. Perhaps to make it easier I could do a more traditional code phrase to encode the faction.
And perhaps I could do remainder 60 or remainder 120 (instead of remainder 100, which is last two digits) and use the timestamp.

OK, I just did the math to add up the totals for all of the roles in the H2P, and realize that I will also need to give you the first letter. There are a lot of roles in the Village faction whose names add up to the same value - in particular, Stalker and Villager both add up to 86, and we would not want to mix up those two.

Other collisions of interest include Harlot/Messiah at 74, Mortician/Purifier at 102, Gravedigger/Maple Wolf at 103, DrunkSeer/NoviceSeer at 115, RuneSmith/Sleepwalker at 127, CryptThief/Protector at 130, Inquisitor/MasonSergeant at 151.
Also, ParanoidSeer/TarotReader at 125.
Luckily, if I give you the first letter, those collisions go away. When I come up with the faction identifiers, I'll also figure out a way to convey that.

In fact, the first letter is probably enough to give you the role outright, or at least give you a few working theories that can tide you over until nightfall. I still want to get the checksum in, though, partly because I'm proud of it, but also because it'll provide a redundancy check on my code - if the sum doesn't match the faction name or first letter I give you, you'll know that I made a mistake.

Message: All right, I'm ready with the code
==== BLOODHOUND CODE ====

1) The message I will attempt to convey is a message of the form "Target is Role". I will be sure to give my check target before the night ends, so the unknown part of the message in the morning will be the "Role" portion.

2) To get the full message across, I will first be conveying the _checksum_ of the message given in step 1. This checksum is found by taking each letter and converting it to a number (A=1, B=2, ..., Z=26) and taking the remainder over 60. This will be broadcast as the _timestamp_ of my first message.

3) The first part of the message itself will indicate the _faction_ of the targeted player. This will be a simple, traditional code: "Good morning" (Village), "Hey all, just got on" (Coven), "All right, another day" (Vampire), "Oh, RIP (name)"/"Hey, no deaths" (Undead), "Hey guys" (BMC), "Hello all" (Neutral)

4) Anything following in the message will be used to disambiguate any roles with the same checksum by including words that start with the first letter of the role, and not including words that start with the first letter of other roles it could be confused with (e.g. if identifying Gravedigger over Maple Wolf, I will include a word that starts with G but not a word that starts with M).

Example 1: If Krombacher is a Villager, I will try to convey the message "Krombacher is Villager". The sum of the letters in this message is 208, so the checksum is 48. This is a village faction, and the role needs to be disambiguated from Stalker (whose checksum is the same). So, I will send my message at XX:48, and it will say "Good morning! My voice isn't doing so hot."

Example 2: If Krombacher is a Succubus, I will try to convey the message "Krombacher is Succubus". The sum of the letters in this message is 231, making the checksum 11. This is the Coven, and the role needs no disambiguation. So, I will send my message at XX:11, and it will say "Hey all, just got on"
